Rate limiting was not found in the three files you shared. None of `app.js`, `routes.js`, or `handlers.js` import or apply any rate limiting middleware (such as `express-rate-limit` or `rate-limiter-flexible`).

That said, I have not seen your full project -- there could be rate limiting at the infrastructure level (reverse proxy, API gateway, load balancer) or in files not shown here (e.g., a separate middleware file, `db.js`, or framework config).

If you want to add it at the Express layer, `express-rate-limit` is the standard approach:

```javascript
// app.js
import rateLimit from 'express-rate-limit';

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // requests per window per IP
});

app.use('/api', limiter);
app.use('/api', router);
```

Worth noting: `createUser` in particular is a mutation endpoint -- POST endpoints that write to a database typically warrant tighter limits than read endpoints to reduce abuse risk.
